The paper focuses on the assessment of computer systems from a cyber-security perspective, which is a core topic in the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The use of weighted averages and ordered weighted averages with evolutionary algorithms suggests a strong connection to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category, which deals with the development of intelligent algorithms and decision-making systems. The paper also discusses the need for tools to support the expert-led process of system-security assessment, which is related to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. The use of aggregation operators and the identification of important components and factors of a cyber-security problem are also relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, which focuses on the development of algorithms that can learn from data. Finally, the paper deals with cyber-security, which is a topic that falls under the cs.CY (Computers and Society) sub-category, which deals with the social and ethical implications of computing technology.
